upon them, nor eject them from their
possessions
,
but that he would immediately
take advice of his council, learned in the
law, conjuring them by the affection which
they
professed
to bear towards him, to be
aiding and
assisting
in all ways, in their
power, towards bringing the
controversy
to an
issue
.
At
this time, the
steward
, to whom
Mr. Bull
entrusted
the care of his
business
,
was not a
person
of that
discernment
and expedition which the exigency of
affairs
required. He had committed divers
blunders in his accounts, and it was
suspected
that he was a defaulter in more
respects
than one. It cannot, therefore,
be expected, that in conducting a
controversy
of this magnitude, he
should
exactly
hit on the right methods, nor employ the
best
